column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Liquid Valve
column168: On May 1, 2015 at 10:50 hours, personnel at CSXT Avon Yard discovered UTLX 903440, a residue UN 1089, Acetaldehyde tank car to have a hissing noise coming from the top fitting protective area. The car was isolated and the Shipper, Vertellus Specialties, Inc. was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2015050100153. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, Summit Environmental Services, LLC. out of Indianapolis, IN was dispatched to the scene. Upon inspection it was determined the A End Liquid Valve was NOT fully closed + the secondary closure plug was NOT tool tight. As a preventative measure the contractor closed the Liquid Valve to stop the leak.  Then they cleaned the threads and installed new Teflon tape to the secondary plug and tightened the plug tool tight.      Cause Code: 242 at 5 points  NARRI: 5 (4 + 5 + 0) x (2 + 0) = 90
column169: No additional comments.

column62: Deterioration or Aging; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: On 05/06/15 at 11:23 hours personnel in the CSXT Boyles Yard discovered GATX10249, a loaded tank car of FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS, N.O.S.(CRUDE SULFATE TURPENTINE, ALPHA-PINENE) leaking from the manway. The car was isolated and the shipper, Gary Harbin, with Resolute FP US Inc., was notified. Hepaco, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the manway gasket cracked and broken. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper. Contractor personnel replaced the manway gasket, closed and secured the manway, and cleaned the outside of the tank car. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.      NAR Cause Code: 209  Manway/ Hinged and bolted  gasket deteriorated    5(5+3+1) x (2+0) = 90 NARRI     Tarrant, Alabama  05/06/15  GATX10249  FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS, N.O.S.(CRUDE SULFATE TURPENTINE, ALPHA-PINENE
column169: The Shipper, Resolute FP US Inc. should ensure that the shipment is properly packaged for safe transport and ensure all gaskets are in good condition.

column168: On May 6, 2015 at 13:19 hours personnel in the CSXT Howell Yard discovered FURX 844044, a loaded covered hopper car of Ammonium Nitrate leaking from the bottom.  The car was isolated and the shipper, CF Industries, was notified (CHEMTREC Report #2015-05-06-00186-00052).  Summit, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found an unloading slide gate not fully closed.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative.  Summit was able to close the slide gate and secure the release.  The car was then observed while switching to ensure that mechanical failure of the car would not cause the gate to reopen.  No further exceptions were noted and the car was released for transportation.  A special switching move was not required.     NARRI: 5(5+1+0) x (3+0) = 90  Cause Code: N/A

column168: On May 11, 2015 at 12:59 hours, personnel at CSXT Stanley Yard discovered a hissing noise coming from the top fitting protective area from TCIX 21095, a residue UN 1789, Hydrochloric Acid Solution tank car. The car was isolated and the Shipper, Universal Well Services c/o RWE Holding Company was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2015051100147. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, Sunpro, Inc. the Toledo Branch office was dispatched to the scene. Upon inspection it was determined the vapor and liquid lines were missing bolts/nuts and that the pressure bracket was lying on the top of the railcar. As a preventative measure, CSX personnel provided replacement bolts/nuts for SUNPRO to utilize. SUNPRO reinstalled the pressure bracket and secured the vapor and liquid lines with the provided bolts/nuts.     A HAZMATHOLD was placed on TCIX 21095 and required an OTMA-3 to continue in transportation to the consignee to be unloaded.    Cause Code: 245 at 2 points, and 333 at 5 points  NARRI: 5 (4 + 5 + 0) x (2 + 0) = 90

column168: During the loading process a Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. driver removed the hose at the completion of loading. While stowing the hose in the hose tray of the trailer the driver noticed residual material leaking from the hose onto the concrete pad. Dispatch was notified and an in house response crew was summoned. The response crew donned the proper PPE and cleaned the released material. The associated clean up materials were containerized and disposed of properly. The Oregon Emergency response System was notified. Operator Russ provided report #2015-1043.
column169: An internal investigation was conducted and it was determined that the cause of the release was directly related to the failure of the driver to fully clear, cap and control the hose at the conclusion of the loading process. The driver was counseled and retrained on operational procedures relating to vacuum tanker loading / unloading.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: Tank car UTLX 68491 in the railyard was reported dripping liquid from its bottom outlet valve (BOV) area and a containment receptacle was placed under UTLX 68491 to catch drippage.   Contract responders inspecting UTLX 68491 reported the liquid drip source was from UTLX 68491's BOV's mounting flange connection. The responders temporarily secured the leak with an application of 'plug n dike' sealant and plastic taped around the BOV flange connection. Afterwards, UTLX 68491 was moved to a location within the railyard to accommodate transfer of the commodity into trucks. The commodity within UTLX 68491 was transferred into trucks without further incident by 0430 hrs. CDT, 5/04/2015. Any remaining 'heel' within UTLX 68491 was removed which eliminated any further commodity from reaching the BOV appurtenances.  Captured spillage was earmarked for appropriate disposal.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Tank car UTLX 211332 departing the rail yard's repair track after air brake related work was completed was reported with commodity stains on its side shell. Inspection of UTLX 211332 indicated that the source of the commodity stain emanated from the UTLX 211332's reclosing pressure relief valve (PRV). Detailed inspection of the McKenzie 165 psi PRV revealed that this PRV sustained a broken stem. The PRV was gagged-off and UTLX 211332 was isolated in the railyard awaiting a replacement PRV to be installed. All spillage evaporated and no ground impact from spillage was observed.

A BNSF unit petroleum crude oil train derailed six loaded tank cars while operating on main track. The cause of this derailment was attributed to a broken wheel plate on the first derailed tank car. A fire ensued engulfing five of the derailed tank cars and all fires were extinguished by 2100 hrs. CDT 5/06/2015. Air monitoring was initiated. Impacted ground soils were excavated and soil sampling initiated.  Derailed tank car TRFX 1224 sustained damage to its bottom outlet valve's outlet nozzle which was sheared-off and the valve closure rotated to an open position releasing commodity. Most spillage was consumed in the surface level pool fire that ensued after the derailment. The remaining commodity within TRFX 1224 was vacuumed and placed into portable frac tanks for future disposal. TRFX 1224 deemed destroyed was cleaned and purged of hazardous material.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: The driver picked up a pre-loaded trailer from the RDW,Inc yard in Columbia SC.  The trailer had been loaded at Clean Harbors (previously Safety Kleen) in Lexington, SC.  The driver checked the load as best he could and securedit straps and load bars and left for the Hebron Ohio delivery point.  On Saturday night (5/30/2015) the driver pulled into the TA i Hebron OH to rest and wait for CH Hebron to open for him to deliver.  As the driver conducted a walk around before calling it a night he noticed a foul smell and further inspection indicated a small at the rear of the trailer and the right side. Driver called RDW Safety Director who had him put absorbent pads out the protect pavement and absorb previously spilled material as well as put an absorbent noodle in trailer to prevent further spillage.  After clean-up it eas noted that the 55 gallon meetal drum had asmall hole inthe upper portion of the drum. The drum was over-packed so that the transport could be completed.
column169: Clean Harbors needs to be more selective of the condition of the packages it uses to load hazardous materials in.  In addition to the drum that leaked, the clean-up crew discovered other pakages that were degraded and also had to be overpacked.  Clean Harbors loaded the defective package in the center of the trailer and the driver was unable to verify condition before accepting load for transport.  Damaged packages or packages with degradation should never be used to transport a hazardous material.

column168: The driver arrived at the plant for loading, at this location plant personnel is responsible for all aspects of loading.  Drivers are not allowed on top of the tank trailer for any reason while on the property.  The driver remained in the cab of the vehicle while the tank trailer was loaded.  He was able to watch the loader  in the mirror of the truck and watched the loader close the dome lid and tighten the wing nuts.  The loader instructed the driver that a seal was placed on the dome lid.  The driver was released from the loading area and he departed from the plant.      Shortly after departing from the plant the driver noticed product spilling from the crash box and down the side of the tank trailer.  He pulled over and the local fire department responded to the scene and cleaned up the release by putting sand over the released product and removed the waste.      Once the driver was able to investigate the dome lid, he found there was "copper like" object in between the dome lid and the dome lid gasket causing a failure in the seal.  Additionally, the driver stated that at the point of the foreign object the dome lid was raised approximately 1/8 of an inch.  The driver was able to remove the foreign object achieving a proper seal.  Once the clean up was complete the driver and trailer were released from the scene.
column169: The driver took responsibility for the release, he stated that he felt he could trust the securement of the tank trailer due to the fact he was able to watch the loader close the dome lid and tighten the wing nuts.  Additionally, the driver was made aware he was not permitted on top of the tank, so he followed plant procedure.      The driver was instructed of the responsibility to ensure the trailer is secure, even if the plant procedures prohibit him from being on top of the trailer.  He was instructed to find the nearest safe place off property to ensure the securement of the trailer.  In addition, the company's progressive disciplinary action was administered, the driver was issued a on-line training video and test addressing load securement.  Finally the details will be discussed at upcoming safety meetings and the details have been sent out to the entire fleet to ensure everyone is aware of the importance of load securement no matter the circumstances.

A Clariant Corporation treater truck was traveling north on US 79.  As the driver approached the intersection of CR 367, a box trailer truck suddenly entered his lane of travel (the northbound lane) because this driver was attempting evasive action to avoid colliding with a stopped vehicle trying to turn left onto CR 367.  The Clariant driver tried to take evasive action but was struck on the driver side bumber.  The Clariant driver skidded off the north bound side of the road into the northbound ditch before colliding with several trees.  The Clariant truck's front axel was ripped off on impact.  The Special Permit portable tank assemply was also ripped off the truck during the collision, and that is the primary reason for the release of Hazardous Material, the physical damage from the impact of the collision.
column169: This was a traffic accident in which Clariant was not at fault.  The Clariant driver acted quickly to minimize injury and damage as much as possible.  The only recommendations at this time are to use this incident as a learning lesson for all Clariant drivers to keep their "eyes on task" and "mind on task" when they are on the road.

column168: On May 20, 2015 at 09:38 hours personnel in the CSXT Erwin Yard discovered an odor in the area of UTLX 667668, a residue tank car of Xylenes.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Eastman Chemical, was notified via CHEMTREC Report 2015-05-20-00165.  HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that vapor was being released from a faulty vacuum relief valve.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative (Julie Brown 423-229-6420).  RESCAR, an AAR qualified mobile repair unit, removed and replaced the faulty vacuum relief valve; subsequently RESCAR performed bubble leak test on the car.  The car was released into transportation.  Special switching move was required.    NARRI: 2(4+1+0) x (2+0) = 20  Cause Code: 1057

column168: On May 27, 2015 at 1620 ET, while the driver of a Trimac CTMV was off-loading and noticed small drips coming from the external QRB valve. Approximately 1 quart of material released during the off-loading phase from the QRB valve. The release was captured in a 1-gallon bucket and taken by the consignee for re-use. The release did not impact the ground below. A cleanup contractor was dispatched to inspect the valve. It was determined by the cleanup contractor that the leak only took place while the valve was opened due to a faulty gasket. No further release took place during the contractor's response. The CTMV was taken to a repair shop to have the QRB valve gasket replaced. There was no waste generated from this response.

column168: AS HE WAS OPENING THE TRAILER AT DOOR 37, TIM(P/T SUPERVISOR) NOTICED A LEAKING PACKAGE NEAR THE DOOR. HE NOTIFIED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS. WHEN I ARRIVED TO THE AREA, I UTILIZED MY DECISION TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSESS THE SITUATION. BECAUSE THE PACKAGE WAS CORROSIVE, I ALTERED MY PPE TO INCLUDE THE SLIVER SHIELD INNER LINERS. I TESTED THE PH OF THE LIQUID & IT WAS APPROX 11. I CONTAINERIZED THE LEAKING PACKAGE TO A LINED SPILL TRAY. I MOVED 3 AFFECTED PACKAGES OUT OF MY WAY. I APPLIED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO THE LIQUID & RETESTED THE PH. I DID THIS UNTIL THE PH WAS BETWEEN 6-9. I THE SOLIDIFIED ANY REMAINING LIQUID WITH CLAY-BASED ABSORBANT. I SWEPT UP ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIALS & PUT IT INTO ANOTHER LINED SPILL TRAY I THEN TOOK ALL THE PACKAGES TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING WHEN I OPENED THE BOX, I FOUND THAT 1 OF THE 4 PLASTIC BOTTLES HAD CRACKED.

column168: ARRIVED WITH PPE ON TO FIND TWO PACKAGES STACKED ONE ON TOP OF THE OTHER OUTSIDE OF BAY 20. THEY WEER BOTH STAINED ON ONE SIDE BUT WERE NOT LEAKING. FOLLOWED DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR CLEANUP AND CONTAINERIZING. ON OPENING PACKAGE, FOUND SOME OF THE LIQUID HAD LEAKED FROM CAPS TO SURROUNDING CARDBOARD CAUSING THE STAIN TO BLEED THROUGH. IT LOOKED AS THOUGH THE PLASTIC "SEAL" BETWEEN CAP AND LIQUID IN TH ECAP HAD DETERIORATED, LEAKING TO THE LEAKAGE. SINCE THESE WERE BOTH FISHER SCI. PACKAGES ALL PRODUCT HAD TO BE DESTROYED. RETURNED TO DMP AREA AND CONTINUED WITH PROCESSING.    ARRIVED WITH PPE ON TO FIND TWO PACKAGES SITTING OUTSIDE OF BAY 20 NWU. column168: THE KENAN TRASNPORT, LLC UNIT TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON FAIRFAX COUNTY PARKWAY IN FAIRFAX, VIRGINIA. THE DRIVER OF THE OTHER VEHICLE LOST CONTROL AND STRUCK THE LEFT SIDE OF THE KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC TRAILER. THE LOADING LINE WAS DAMAGED AND ALLOWED APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS OF GASOLINE TO BE RELEASED. MOST OF THE GASOLINE WAS CAPTURED IN A CONTAINER. THE FAIRFAX COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM ASSISTED WITH THE CLEAN-UP. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 7:20 AM A CALL FROM A NORFOLK AND SOUTHERN ENGINEER TO THE RAIL YARD WAS MADE ABOUT A TANK CAR WITH VAPOR EMANATING FROM IT. THE RAIL YARD NOTIFIED THE FAIRFIELD FIRE DEPARTMENT. TRUCKS WERE DISPATCHED. THE RAILCAR IN QUESTION WAS ON OUR RAIL SPUR WITH 3 OTHER HCI FULL RAIL CARS AND 2 H2SO4 RAIL CARS (1 FULL AND 1 EMPTY). THE LEAKING CAR WAS THE 5TH ONE BACK FROM OUR GATE WHICH ALSO SERVED AS OUR OBSERVATION POINT. THE GREATER CINCINNATI HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE TEAM WAS ACTIVATED BY THE FAIRFIELD INCIDENT COMMANDER. AT 7:34 AM TOM RILEY WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT, AT 7:37 AM CRAIG OWEN WAS NOTIFIED. AFTER OBSERVING THE CAR FROM A DISTANCE A WHITE VAPOR WAS NOTICED EFFERVESCING FROM THE TOP OF THE RAIL CAR.  AT 8:24 AM T. RILEY WAS GIVEN AN UPDATE. AT 9:28 AM JOE CATAMO FROM CSX RESPONSE TEAM WAS ADVISED OF THE SITUATION AND HE OFFERED THEIR ASSISTANCE IF IT WAS NECESSARY.    ONCE THE HAZ-MAT RESPONSE TEAM WAS ON SITE AND THE LEAK WAS DETERMINED TO BE MINOR, 2 USALCO EMPLOYEES DONNED PROPER PPE WITH 4 OTHERS FROM THE GREATER CINCINNATI HAZ-MAT RESPONSE TEAM WERE SENT TO WALK TO THE CAR, CLIMB THE LADDER AND IDENTIFY WHERE THE LEAK WAS LOCATED.  UPON 1ST INSPECTION THEY COULD NOT TELL WHERE THE LEAK ORIGINATED DUE TO THE RESIDUE LEFT FROM THE HCI VAPOR REACTION WITH MOISTURE IN THE AIR. AFTER THE VAPOR WAS REDUCED NATURALLY, A SECOND ATTEMPT WAS MADE AND THEY OBSERVED THAT AN AREA AT THE GASKET SEAL ON THE LOADING MANWAY AS LEAKING. THE DOME AREA OF THE RAIL CAR HAD SOME PHYSICAL DAMAGE, NOT FROM THIS LEAK, IT WAS NOT APPARENT WHEN, HOW OR WHERE THIS DAMAGE OCCURRED. IT MAY HAVE BEEN RELATED TO CAUSING THIS LEAK AS IT WAS FELT THE COVER SUFFERED DAMAGE AND MAYBE GOT MISALIGNED, OR GASKET GOT MOVED CAUSING IT TO BE COMPROMISED. FURTHERMORE, THE OPERATOR WAS ABLE TO REMOVE THE HANDLE ON THE DOME LID QUITE EASILY WHEN INVESTIGATING THE RAIL CAR. THIS LEAD TO THE ASSUMPTION THAT THE DAMAGE WAS RECENT AND WAS A POSSIBLE CONTRIBUTOR TO THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK. AT ABOUT 10:10 AM ALL GATHERED TO DISCUSS THE FINDINGS AND POSSIBLE SOLUTIONS TO AMELIORATE THE LEAK.  IT WAS DECIDED THAT THE BEST OPTION WAS TO MOVE THE RAIL CAR TO THE OFF-LOADING RACK AND TRANSFER THE MATERIAL TO STORAGE. WHILE THE CARS WERE BEGIN MOVED INTO THE USALCO FAIRFIELD FACILITY, FROM THE RAIL SPUR OUTSIDE OUR GATE, USING USALCO EQUIPMENT AND USALCO EMPLOYEES, I NOTIFIED THE OHIO EPA AT 10:23 AM AND THE LOCAL EMERGENCY PLANNING COMMISSION OF BUTLER COUNTY AT 10:28 AM.    ONCE THE RAIL CAR WAS MOVED INTO POSITION WITH USALCO EQUIPMENT AND BY USALCO EMPLOYEES, WE HOOKED UP THE VENT LINE TO OUR SCRUBBER. AT THIS TIME LITTLE TO NO LEAK WAS OBSERVED AT THE LOADING MECHANISM AND GASKET AREA. WHEN THE OPERATOR OPENED THE VENT LINE IT WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN LIQUID. HE CLOSED THE VENT VALVE AND WE DISCUSSED AMONG OURSELVES WHAT WAS OBSERVED. WE DECIDED TO ELEVATE THE VENT LINE SO ANY VAPOR WILL RISE AND LIQUID WOULD NOT EASILY TRAVEL THE LINE TO SCRUBBER AND POSSIBLY OVERWHE
column169: RAIL CAR WAS RETURNED TO THE SUPPLIER ASHTA CHEMICAL FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION AND CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: On May 27, 2015 at 00:15 hours personnel in the CSXT Wauhatchie Yard discovered RCRX 2222, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric Acid, leaking from the top of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Reagent Chemical, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report 2015-27-07-00022).  HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the fill hole cover securement bolts were less than tool tight and the vapor valve flange bolts less than tool tight.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative (Kevin Callais 409-460-1273).  The noted bolts/nuts were secured tool tight.  Reagent Chemical arranged for an AAR qualified mobile repair unit to perform a successful bubble leak test prior to the car being put back in transportation to ensure that field repairs were adequate and the car was free of leaks.  A special switching move was required.    NARRI: 5(5+5+0) x (2+0) = 100  Cause Code: 363, 224

column168: A van trailer containing a hazardous material was being returned to the original shipper.  During the course of transportation, the vehicle stopped at Clean Harbor’s Laurel Maryland Service Center pending continued transportation.  While parked in a secured location, one Intermediate Bulk Package experienced a release from a bottom valve that resulted in a release of vapors from the package that exited the vehicle and crossed the property line of our facility.      Facility personnel activated their internal emergency response plan and notified local authorities as well as internal spill response teams.  Upon arrival of local Fire Department, a “shelter in place” order was issued to those businesses and homes located downwind of the vapor plume which lasted approximately 1.5 hours.  During this time representatives from the Fire Department and Clean Harbors developed a response plant to not only recover the material that had escaped from the package but also a plan to re containerize the remaining packages into non bulk stainless steel containers.  Due to the hazards presented by the material in question, these activities were performed with the support and guidance of local authorities over a 48 hour period.  All spill debris and re containerized product was then prepared and shipped to a fully permitted waste management facility for treatment and disposal.  IN addition, activities were conducted at the site to remediate and decontaminate all affected areas. This was reported to the NRC and the  Maryland DEP # 0800 053015
column169: It is believed that the original shipper inadvertently shipped fuming sulfuric acid rather than the less concentrated sulfuric acid scheduled for acceptance. In order to prevent a recurrence, Clean Harbors will require that the customer confirm, in writing, that the material being offered for transportation has been inspected and it meets the specification of the material agreed to be accepted.  This confirmation will also certify that the material is prepared for transportation in accordance with all applicable Department of Transportation  requirements. Honeywell has also implemented the following:   1. Honeywell is completing a thorough investigation to the root causes of this incident involving the improper loading of a commercial product into tote containers, subsequent shipment and ultimate off-site incident.  2. Enhanced administrative controls have been and will continue to be implemented for any future product transfers:  Verification of equipment contents, proper sampling and analysis supervised by owning area leadership, substantiation of contractor activities, verbal and written communication to ensure that transfers are legitimate and safe.  3. Enhanced training for all on-site and off-site parties involved in the movement of products, residues, and any wastes.  4. Continued and enhanced DOT training to verify correct packaging of identified hazardous materials.  5. Enhanced communication with Honeywell HSE functional groups when any/all chemical transfers are imminent.  6. Continued development of emergency response personnel and contractors to hazards and technical responses (equipment, strategies, training) for major chemicals at the Hopewell site.  Expanding emergency response contractor base.

column168: Approximately 55 gallons of UN1261 Nitromethane released from a 55 gallon drum due to a puncture in the bottom of the drum caused by an unknown object. The release impacted the trailer floor and evaporated into the atmosphere. The empty damaged drum was containerized in a salvage drum for pending disposal.

A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc arrived at customer's location to pick up a scheduled load.  Prior to the trailer was being loaded, the driver noticed a compromised drum.  The company immediately overpacked the drum and secured in van trailer.  The driver then proceeded to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the in-transit phase, it was discovered that approximately 20 gallons of material had  escaped from a pinhole leak that had developed in the container. Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the compromised  container into a suitable salvage drum. In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and  placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was observed. Drivers will continue to inspect each container during staging period as well as before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity. IN addition, the shipper has been advised of the situation and have been asked to inspect all container used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required  specifications.

column168: On May 22, 2015, a 330-gallon tote containing UN1210 printing ink was found to be leaking while located on an R&L Carriers dock. The camlock seal was worn allowing approximately one cup of material to leak to the concrete floor. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site and replaced the faulty seal. column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Gasket
column168: On 28 May 2015 a load of GRAMOXONE SL 2.0 275 Gallon totes was delivered to the Nickey Warehouse and during the unloading process it was discovered that 6 of the totes in the shipment were found leaking around the Gem Cap. The seal was removed from each tote, the Gem Cap was then removed, the material that was found leaking around the gem cap was cleaned (removed). The Gem Caps were then placed on the tote and a new seal was installed on each tote. The totes where then driven around the warehouse with a forklift to determine if any material was leaking from the totes and no leaking material was found to be leaking from around the Gem Cap. As a result of the incident it was also found that the sealing of the tank opening are uneven and inconsistent and have also contributed to the totes leaking when the Gem Cap is torqued on the tote.
column169: It was determined that updated closing instructions from the manufacture of the tote had not been communicated to the production location and the production location was only applying 75 ft/lb of torque to the Gem Cap, when in fact per the updated closing instructions 120 ft/lbs of torque was required to properly seal the Gem Cap on the tote. The production site is work with the tote manufacture to correct the uneven and inconsistent sealing surfaces on the tote so that a proper seal may be achieved.

column168: A Maryland Chemical driver was using an electric pallet jack to move a 275 gallon IBC to the rear of a dry van where it was to be unloaded by a forklift.  The truck and dry van were on a level surface.  When the pallet jack got to the rear of the truck the tote slide off the forks and off the truck landing on it's side.  The tote split on the top and all product was released in a matter of minutes.
column169: Company procedure is to now position the tote away from the end of the trailer and have the forklift operator move the tote to the final lift point for safe removal.  Drivers have been trained on this new procedure and also retrained on the use of an electric pallet jack.

column168: A FRA Hazardous Material Inspector inspecting rail cars in the railyard reported observing tank car GATX 53838 emanating a commodity odor with residue on the tank top and side, as well as, atop the valve housing plate which emanated from the affixed vacuum relief valve (VRV). Apparently, the VRV was stuck open/malfunctioned allowing commodity to escape from the VRV. BNSF mechanical responders removed the faulty VRV and secured a plug in the VRV vacated orifice. Spillage on GATX 53838 was wiped. .
column169: The shipper/offeror must submit a request to FRA for an one-time movement approval to move the tank car to shop for repair.

column168: TANK CAR PTRX 7007 IN THE RAILYARD WAS REPORTED WITH ICING ON ITS SIDE EQUIPMENT/OPERATING COMPARTMENT (CABINET). BNSF MECHANICAL RESPONDERS INSPECTING PTRX 7007 REPORTED THE LIQUID LINE VALVE WAS PARTIALLY OPEN WITH ITS CLOSURE CAP NOT SECURE. THE RESPONDER CLOSED THE VALVE WHEEL FOR THE LIQUID LINE (APPROXIMATELY 1/2 INCH TURN). THE RESPONDER THEN TIGHTENED AND SECURED THE CLOSURE CAP (1/2 INCH BY HAND AND ANOTHER 1/2 INCH WITH A WRENCH). AFTERWARDS, THE VAPORIZING LIQUID RELEASE ENDED.
column169: ENSURE SHIPPER'S PRE-TRIP INSPECTION PROCESS IS FULLY IMPLEMENTD AND VALIDATED AS IT RELATES TO THE TOTAL SECUREMENT AND MECHANICAL FITNESS OF ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS.

column168: On May 26, 2015, a 55-gallon drum located on an R&L Carriers trailer was found to be leaking due to a nail puncture. Approximately two gallons of product was released to the trailer floor. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site for response activities. The damaged drum was placed into an 85-gallon salvage drum for continued transportation. The trailer floor was neutralized and granular absorbent was applied. All waste was collected and containerized for pending disposal.

column168: On 05/17/2015 A Dupre Logistics tanker truck was making a delivery of gasoline to a Valero gas station when a passenger vehicle ran over the transfer hoses connected to the UST. The passenger vehicle tore the hose away from the connectors causing the release of approximately 50 gallons of fuel. Onsite personnel and the FD contained the release with granular absorbents. A contractor was dispatched to collect the and clean the rest.

A 55 gallon drum of a UN1993, Gyptron T-315, Flammable liquid, was found to be leaking in a Landstar trailer. The driver was making a pretrip inspection when the leak was discovered coming from the trailer. A crew was dispatched to unload the trailer and find the leaking drum. The leaking drum was found to have a faulty bottom seam. The released material was cleaned and the drum overpacked.

14 used totes of this material were being returned to a container company for cleaning and reuse. Upon delivery it was found that one of the totes had residual material in it and the bottom valve was left open. Approximately 3 gallons of the material leaked into the trailer and onto the pavement. There was no damage to the tote only a valve that was left open. An environmental crew closed the valve and cleaned the release inside the trailer and on the pavement.

Upon arrival at the origin terminal, the drum was discovered leaking inside the trailer. The drum was damaged due to a lack of blocking and bracing of freight. Another skid on the trailer slid into the drum causing damage. The absorbent materials and the damaged drum were placed into an overpack for later disposal. Due to the hazard of material the package specifications were not able to be obtained.
column169: The driver responsible for securing this drum for transit was disciplined per company policy. This incident will also be used as an example in future driver meetings.

column168: A pail of UN3266 Corrosive liquid, Inorganic, NOS (Potassium Hydroxide, Sodium Metasilicate) was damaged during dock operations at a Con-way facility. A forklift punctured the pail during dock operations, leading to the release of approximately 2 gallons from the 5-gallon pail. Con-way terminal personnel overpacked the pail and cleaned the release. No soils, drains or waterways were impacted.

column168: TANKER WAS BEING LOADED WITH 15% SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE. A LEAK DEVELOPED BETWEEN THE BARREL AND INTERNAL VALVE. APPROXIMATELY ONE QUART LEAKED ONTO PAVEMENT. IT WAS CLEANED UP IMMEDIATELY. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON WAS COLLECTED IN A BUCKET. THE MATERIAL WAS TRANSFERRED FROM THE TANKER TO ANOTHER TANKER WITH A PUMP. THE TANKER WAS WASHED AND SENT IN FOR REPAIRS. THE INTERNAL VALVE WAS EXAMINED AND IT WAS DETERMINED A GASKET WAS MISSING. LINE 25.1 INDICATES THE GASKET FAILED. THE GASKET DID NOT ACTUALLY FAIL; IT WAS MISSING. JUST PRIOR TO THE INCIDENT, ON MAY 5, 2015, A THIRD PARTY MAINTENANCE SERVICE PROVIDE COMPLETED VIK (VISUAL, INTERNAL, LEAK) TESTING ON TANKER 2631. THE TANKER INTIALLY FAILED THE LEAK TEST BECAUSE THE INTERNAL VALVE LEAKED. THEY REPLACED THE INTERNAL VALVE BUT DID NOT INSTALL A NEEDED GASKET BETWEEN THE TANKER AND THE INTERNAL VALVE.  THEY THEN LEAK TESTED FROM THE INTERNAL VALVE TO THE EXTERNAL VALVE AND FOUND NO LEAKS. THEY DID NOT, HOWEVER, TEST FROM THE TANKER TO THE INTERNAL, WHICH WOULD HAVE DETECTED THE LEAK THAT CAUSED THE INCIDENT.

column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, TYPE A PACKAGE NON-SPECIAL FORM, NON FISSILE OR FISSILE-EXCEPTED
column168: THE PACKAGE WAS ORIGINALLY SHIPPED ON WABILL 773466545498 BY RED RIVER PHARMACY, LITTLE ROCK, ARKANSAS ON APRIL 27, 2015 TO RED RIVER PHARMACY, JONEBORO, ARKANSAS.  IT TRAVELED BY HIGHWAY FROM LITTLE ROCK, ARKANSAS, TO THE FEDEX EXPRESS MEMPHIS, HUB ARRIVING ON APRIL 28, 2015.  IT DEPARTED BY GROUND MEMPHIS ON APRIL 29, 2015 ARRIVING AT THE FEDEX JONESBORO STATION ON APRIL 29, 2015.  THE PACKAGE WAS REFUSED BY RED RIVER PHARMACY BECAUSE OF LATE ARRIVAL AND WAS RETURNED BY GROUND TO THE SHIPPER ON APRIL 30, 2015 ON WAYBILL 773493525835. IT ARRIVED AT THE FEDEX EXPRESS MEMPHIS HUB ON MAY 2, 2015 BY GROUND BACK TO JONESBORO, ARKANSAS. ON MAY 4, 2015 THE PACKAGE WAS SENT TO RED RIVER PHARMACY, LITTLE ROCK, ON WAYBILL 773514909750 BY GROUND ARRIVING IN MEMPHIS AT 12:04 AM MAY 5, 2015; DEPARTING MEMPHIS AT 4:07 AM MAY 5, 2015 AND ARRIVING AT THE FEDEX EXPRESS LITTLE ROCK STATION AT 7:46 AM MAY 5, 2015. THE FEDEX EXPRESS LITTLE ROCK STATION NOTED THE PACKAGE WAS DAMAGED AND REPORTED IT TO FEDEX EXPRESS DANGEROUS GOODS ADMINISTRATION, WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED DR. ROY PARKER, FEDEX EXPRESS, RADIATION PHYSICS CONSULTANT. BECAUSE OF THE NATURE OF THE PACKAGE DAMAGE AND RADIATION READINGS DR. PARKER, REQUESTED THE ASSISTANCE OF THE SHIPPER RED RIVER PHARMACY. RED RIVER PHARMACY RESPONDED AND DETERMINED THAT ON OF TWO I-131 CAPSULES WERE MISSING. THE ACTIVITY OF EACH I-131 CAPSULE ON MARCH 5, 2015 WAS 3 MCI. FEDEX EXPRESS REPORTED THE MISSING 3 MCI I-131 CAPSULE TO THE ARKANSAS RADIATION CONTROL AGENCY. THE ARKANSAS RADIATION CONTROL AGENCY AND RED RIVER PHARMACY SURVEYED THE FEDEX EXPRESS LITTLE ROCK STATION, INCLUDING THE ULD WHICH BROUGHT THE SUBJECT PACKAGE FROM MEMPHIS TO LITTLE ROCK. THE RESULTS WERE NEGATIVE. THE TRAILER WHICH TRANSPORTED THE PACKAGE FROM MEMPHIS TO LITTLE ROCK HAD LEFT THE FEDEX EXPRESS LITTLE ROCK STATION SO ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO SURVEY THE TRAILER WHEN IT ARRIVED IN MEMPHIS. THE RESULTS WERE NEGATIVE.   THE TENNESSEE RADIATION CONTROL AGENCY WAS NOTIFIED. THE LITTLE ROCK OUTBOUND SLIDE AREA WAS SURVEYED BY FEDEX EXPRESS AT THE MEMPHIS HUB AND THE RESULTS WERE NEGATIVE. THE ARKANSAS RADIATION CONTROL AGENCY SURVEYED THE FEDEX EXPRESS JONESBORO STATION ON MAY 7, 2015, AND THE RESULTS WERE NEGATIVE. ON MAY 8, 2015 IN CONJUNCTION OF ADDITIONAL PERSONNEL BEING INTERVIEWED THE LITTLE ROCK SLIDE AREA SURVEYED WAS EXPANDED AND THE I-131 CAPSULE WAS FOUND IN ITS VIAL UNDAMAGED.  ON THE DATE THE I-131 CAPSULE WAS 2.35 MCI. THE I-131 CAPSULE WILL BE STORED BY FEDEX EXPRESS UNTIL IT DECAYS BELOW A LEVEL FOR TRASH DISPOSAL.

column168: Environmental Release – 5/27/15  Coles County    At approximately 7:30 am, Kemp office manager Cathie Adcock phoned Pat Titus to indicate their office had been called by Charleston Fire Chief, Pat Goodwin. He indicated the Mattoon and Lincoln Fire Protection District were called out to a farmstead south of Mattoon where four 1,000 gallon nurse tanks were parked, two tanks attached to one another. There was a fifth tank that was attached to the sidedress toolbar, which was attached to the tractor.    Titus quickly returned the call to Chief Goodwin (ph. 217-345-2134). Goodwin said they received a call about 2:30 am and the tanks were blowing 6-8’ streams. Goodwin stated he knew that NH3 valves will loosen up with the change of temperatures. He asked if we planned to consider this a criminal activity, of which I replied “yes.” He also asked Titus to find out when the farmer left the field the night before    At 7:41 am, Titus made a call in to the National Response Center and spoke with Petty Officer Morley. Report # 1117672 was issued. PO Morley asked about the address of Gary Kuhns (farmer) and a phone number for him. He also asked about the amount of product lost.    At 7:54 am, Titus called the Illinois Emergency Management Association and spoke to Josh Deheve. He issued report # H-2015-0572.    He asked about:   Wind speed/direction   Tank size   Amount released   Kuhns’ address and phone number    At 8:02 am, Titus called the Coles County LEPC (ph # 348-0581) but there was no answer and no voicemail. Titus tried again at 9:13 am with no results. Titus mentioned this later in the day to Chief Goodwin, and he said yes…they were aware of the release as the state had contacted them (due to me calling it in to the IEMA).    Titus called Mike Turner about the release. She then emailed a summary of what she knew of the release to interested parties (Turner, Romito, Busby, Dollins from Illini FS, and Cring, Frye, and Zmolek from GROWMARK).   Titus went over to Kemp to get copies of the scale tickets from office manager Adcock. She received a call from Illini FS employee, Terry Warner, who was at the farmsite. Warner asked about removing the tanks. Titus said she wanted to leave them there until scene was investigated. Turner told Adcock he would be down to the farmstead but it would be another 45 minutes.    After leaving Kemp, Titus received a phone call from IDOA NH3 inspector, Dennis Beckmeier. Beckmeier said it would be around 2 pm before he could get there.    Titus went to the location off of Old State Rd. in Mattoon. Two tanks hooked together were on the driveway south of the house, and another two tanks hooked together, with hitch pointed to the east, in the grass to the slight northeast of the other tanks. It was visibly obvious from the dead grass of the release. One could see the direction of the plume the night before, based on the burned leaves of the corn plants. Titus estimated the more damaged corn was approximately ½-3/4 acre with no

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE CARDBOARD CARTON, WHICH CONTAINED FOUR (4)-1 GALLON BOTTLES OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID, 34% WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT. AREA WAS ISOLATED, AND GREENVILLE FD WAS DISPATCHED TO ASSESS. UPON ARRIVAL ON SITE, A STRONG ODOR WAS COMING FROM THE TRAILER, AND FREE LIQUID HAD RELEASED THROUGH TRAILER FLOOR TO ASPHALT SURFACE BENEATH. DUE TO HEAVY RAINFALL AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT, PRODUCT RELEASED TO THE GROUND SURFACE WAS UNRECOVERABLE. ADVANCED ENVIRONMENTAL OPTIONS WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. UPON ARRIVAL ON SITE, GREENVILLE FD AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WERE ON SITE TO SECURE THE AREA. AEO INVESTIGATED THE TRAILER, AND DETERMINED THAT ONE CARTON HAD BEEN PUNCTURED. PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED TO CARDBOARD INSIDE TRAILER. PER DIRECTION FROM SOUTH CAROLINA DHEC SITE INSPECTOR, MATT RAVEN, AEO WAS RELEASED FROM THE SITE, AND NO FURTHER ACTION WAS REQUIRED. WILSON TRUCKING PERSONNEL WERE INSTRUCTED TO CONTAINERIZE THE EMPTY BOTTLES AND CARDBOARD CARTON INTO A RECOVERY DRUM, PENDING DISPOSITION. DUE TO THE NATURE OF THE PRODUCT AND DILUTED COMPOSITION, THERE WAS NO THREAT TO HUMAN HEALTH OR THE ENVIRONMENT. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.
column169: WILSON TRUCKING CORPORATION WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND REINFORCE SAFE HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column168: Upon arrival at the destination terminal, 4 pails were discovered leaking. After further investigation it was determined that due to a lack of blocking and bracing the pails were punctured by other freight shifting in transit. The damaged pails a absorbent material were placed into overpacks for later disposal. Due to the hazard of material the package specifications were not able to be obtained.
column169: This incident will be used as a talking point during future dock meetings to stress the importance of properly blocking and bracing freight for transit.

column168: May 26, 2015 Sandhu Growers, 301 Fulkerth Rd Crows Landing, CA  - cause of overfill, Human Error. Driver talked to another driver prior to going to customer site and was told that the tanks were 2 x 5000 gallon tanks. The delivery called for 4000 gallons of Diesel #2, driver stuck the tank which had 4 inches in it. According to the 5000 gallon tank chart the load should have fit. The problem ended up being, that the tanks were only 4000 gallon tanks.      The delivery invoice indicated in the notes area that there were two 3500 gallon tanks plumbed together at this site. Driver failed to pay attention to this note or call into dispatch to verify delivery. There was an overflow of approximately 20 gallons onto soil around the tank via the tank vent. Neither SC Fuels CTMV nor the customers tank were damaged.  There was no immediate threat to public and the Regional HSE Manager was immediately notified, he went to site and coordinated cleanup of the site. Stanislaus Co Hazardous Materials Division- Robert Reiss (209 534-6335) was contacted to report spill and CA Office of Emergency Services was notified and an incident number assigned Cal- OES 15-2918.     Spill was on dirt,  11 barrels of contaminated soil were removed. A soil sample was taken under the direction of Stanislaus Co Hazardous Materials specialist Amber Minami (209 409-4264). Clean up was deemed successful. Safety Kleen Systems Inc (Manifest Tracking #004764566) picked up the contaminated soil for proper disposal.
column169: SC Fuels has a customer base with above ground tanks. It was determined that many of these tanks do not have tank capacity indicators on them. SC Fuels delivery invoices are to include tank size information.     An initiative to label tank capacity and maximum fill is under way. This would include tank charts for each tank that are left at the tank for delivery drivers reference.      Drivers have been reminded to check the notes section of the delivery invoices for tank information as well as call in if in doubt regarding tank size

On 5/23/2015, a 407 model tanker carrying 5,700 gallons of UN2810 released approximately 0.5 gallon of product onto the asphalt roadside due to a missing top washout cap. The release duration is estimated to be instantaneous with another driver notifying the driver during the occurrence. The top washout cap was replaced and tested prior to the tanker being released. When the release occurred the product  impacted the tanker along with relatively small area on the asphalt roadway which was cleaned up utilizing absorbents and containerized into 30-gallon drum of impacted absorbents, spent PPE, pads, and decon rags)for transport off-site and disposal. The pH results of testing the roadway were within neutral ranges between 5-6. The cause of the missing washout cap has not been determined. In addition, the cleanup contractor visited the Site prior loading location following clean-up activities and no signs were observed or reported by facility representatives.

column168: PVS-NOLWOOD DELIVERY DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE CUSTOMER INTENDING TO TRANSFER APPROXIMATELY 11,500 POUNDS OF 50% SODIUM HYDDROXIDE FROM FOUR INTERMEDIATE BULK CONTAINERS TO A CUSTOMER OWNED STORAGE TANK WITH A PUMP. THE DRIVER ARRIVED ONE DAY BEFORE THE CUSTOMER REQUESTED. THE CUSTOMER CHECKED HIS TANK AND DETERMINED THERE WAS ENOUGH ROOM TO RECEIVE THE DELIVERY. AT THE END OF THE DELIVERY, THE CUSTOMER TANK OVERFLOWED. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF MATERIAL OVERFLOWED FROM THE TANK ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE BUILDING HOUSING THE TANK. THE DRIVER BLEW HIS LINES BACK INTO THE IBC AND THE CUSTOMER EMPLOYEE CLEANED UP THE OVERFLOWED MATERIAL.    THE CAUSES OF THE RELEASE WERE:  1) FAILURE OF PVS-NOLWOOD TO USE STANDARD AND UNAMBIGUOUS LANGUAGE WHEN SCHEDULING DELIVERIES, AND  2) FAILURE OF THE CUSTOMER TO ACCURATELY VERIFY THERE WAS ENOUGH ROOM IN THE TANK.    THE TRANSPORTATION PACKAGE DID NOT FAIL.
column169: PVS-NOLWOOD CUSTOMER SERVICE INTENDS TO STANDARDIZE LANGUAGE TO PREVENT MISCOMMUNICATION LEADING TO EARLY DELIVERIES.  THE METHOD THE CUSTOMER USES TO ENSURE THEIR TANK HAS ENOUGH ROOM TO RECEIVE DELIVERIES IS INTERNAL TO THE CUSTOMER.

column168: UPON UNLOADING AT THE LME DOCK, IT WAS OBSERVED THAT A STRONG ODOR WAS COMING FROM THE TRAILER UPON OPENING THE DOORS. IT WAS OBSERVED THAT A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. EMPLOYEES WERE INSTRUCTED TO CLOSE THE DOORS, AND AWAIT THE ARRIVAL OF A RESPONSE TEAM.  UPON THE ARRIVAL OF THE RESPONSE TEAM, SHIPPING DOCUMENTS WERE REVIEWED TO DETERMINE WHAT WAS BEING TRANSPORTED ON THE TRAILER. RESPONSE PERSONNEL DONNED PROPER PPE, AND BEGAN THE INITIAL ASSESSMENT. RESPONSE PERSONNEL DETERMINED THAT ONE (1) DRUM OF TOXIC LIQUID WAS ESTIMATED TO BE 1/8" OF AN INCH IN LENGTH. THE DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND OFF-LOADED IN PREPARATION FOR CLEAN UP ACTIVITIES. RESPONSE PERSONNEL DETERMINED THAT THE FLOOR HAD BEEN IMPACTED WITH PRODUCT, AS WELL AS WOODEN PALLETS THAT THE DRUMS WERE ON AND OTHER PALLETIZED CARGO. RESPONSE PERSONNEL OFF-LOADED NUMEROUS CARGO PALLETS TO INSURE THAT ALL IMPACTED SURFACES WERE REMOVED AND CLEANED PROPERLY. SIX (6) PALLETS IN TOTAL HAD BEEN IMPACTED BY THE LEAKING PRODUCT, WHICH WERE REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER, CARGO REPACKAGED, AND THE PALLETS CUT UP AND PLACED IN 55 GALLON DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL AT A LATER DATE. GRANULAR ABSORBENTS AND PADDING WAS UTILIZED IN A CLEANING THE IMPACTED TRAILER FLOOR. ONCE COMPLETE, ALL IMPACTED ABSORBENTS AND MATERIALS WERE PLACED IN 55 GALLON DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL AT A LATER DATE. ONCE COMPLETE, THE CLEAN UP EFFORTS WERE INSPECTED BY LME PERSONNEL, AND DEEMED ACCEPTABLE. RESPONSE PERSONNEL DEMOBILIZED AFTER APPROXIMATELY SIX (6) HOURS ON SITE.
column169: It is suggested that the manufacturer and shipper conduct a more thorough inspection of drums before product is placed in drums, and again before the product is shipped.

column168: WHILE RIG/TRAILER WAS TRAVELING WEST ON I-10 BETWEEN RIVERSIDE AVE. AND SIERRA ST. AT AROUND 11:00AM ON 5/28/2015, A PASSING DRIVER GESTURED TO THE RIG/TRAILER DRIVER THAT SOMETHING IS NOT RIGHT BEHIND THE TRAILER. THE RIG/TRAILER DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PULLED OVER THE SIDE OF THE FREEWAY AND UPON SAFELY STOPPING, HE PROCEEDED TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER AND OBSERVED THAT A MOIST POWDERY-SUBSTANCE WAS ESCAPING FROM UNDER THE TRAILER'S REAR DOOR.  THE DRIVER OPENED A BAG OF ABSORBENT AND POSITIONED IT DIRECTLY UNDERNEATH THE ESCAPING MATERIAL. THE TOTAL MATERIAL THAT ESCAPED FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER IS ESTIMATED TO BE LESS THAN A POUND.  UPON OPENING ONE OF THE TRAILER'S REAR DOORS, DRIVER NOTICED THAT A CARDBOARD BOX LINED WITH PLASTIC HAD RUPTURED IN ON CORNER WHERE THE MOIST-POWDERY MATERIAL ORIGINATED.  RESPONSE CREWS FROM BOTH SHIPPER AND TRANSPORTED WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE AND UPON ARRIVAL THEY IMMEDIATELY PROCEEDED TO TRANSFER ALL THE MATERIAL FROM THE RUPTURED CONTAINER TO ANOTHER DOT-APPROVED CONTAINER.

column168: THE DRIVER WAS MAKING A MINIBULK DELIVERY OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE (BLEACH) AT THE LIFETIME FITNESS GYM.  HE HAD PUMPED OFF THE DESIRED AMOUNT OF PRODUCT AND WAS PREPARING TO PURGE THE SUPPLY HOSE WITH AIR.  WHEN HE BEGAN TO PURGE THE LINE A FITTING ON THE TOP OF THE BULK TANK BEGAN TO LEAK PRODUCT.  THE DRIVER QUICKLY RELEASED THE AIR PRESSURE TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER LOSS OF PRODUCT.  THE DRIVER THEN DEPLOYED HIS EMERGENCY SPILL KIT TO PREVENT THE SPREAD OF PRODUCT IN THE PARKING LOT.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITHIN A FEW SHORT MINUTES AND THE CALL WAS PUT IN FOR A CLEAN UP CREW TO RESPOND.
column169: THE FITTING IN QUESTION WAS CRACKED AT THE TIGHTENING RING.  IT IS UNSURE IF IT WAS CRACKED FROM OVERTIGHTENING IN THE REPAIR SHOP OR IF IT WAS A FACTORY FAILURE. ALL VALVES ARE CHECKED AT YEARLY INSPECTIONS AND CERTIFICATIONS.

column168: ON MAY 25, 2015 AT APPROXIMATELY 1345, AND EAST PENN LOGISTICS, LLC BOX TRUCK WAS DRIVING EAST ON I-76 AROUND MILE MARKER 286, A CINTAS VAN WAS SLOWING UP IN RIGHT LANE ASIDE OF THE EAST PENN LOGISTICS BOX TRUCK. THERE WAS AN ERB TRACTOR TRAILER PULLED OFF ON THE SIDE OF THE ROAD GETTING SERVICE. THE EAST PENN LOGISTIC BOX TRUCK IN THE PASSENGER SIDE REAR, PUSHING THE EAST PENN DRIVER INTO THE CINTAS VAN. THE JB HUNT TRUCK KEPT SLIDING PAST TO THE SIDE OF THE ERB TRUCK. THE ROAD WAS CLOSED FOR ABOUT AN HOUR UNTIL THEY COULD GET IT CLEANED UP SO THAT ONE LANE WAS OPEN. PHOTOS ATTACHED.  THE EAST PENN LOGISTICS LLC TRUCK WAS CARRYING SPENT LEAD ACID BATTERIES. DUE TO THE CRASH, BATTERY ELECTROLYTE LEAKED ONTO THE ROAD FROM THE CRACKED/SMASHED BATTERIES. ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS PUT DOWN TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. THIS WAS COLLECTED AND PUT INTO A 30 GALLON DRUM FOR DISPOSAL. THE TRUCK CONTAINING THE BATTERIES WAS INSPECTED ON SITE, BUT WAS TOWED OFFSITE FOR CLEANUP SO THE PA TURNPIKE COULD REOPEN THE ROADWAY. THE CLEANUP SERVICE CONTINUED WITH THE CLEANUP AT THE TOWING FACILITY. DAMAGED AND LEAKING BATTERIES WERE PLACED INTO 55 GALLON POLY DRUM FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. THE BATTERIES THAT WERE NOT DAMAGED OR LEAKING WERE LEFT ON THE PALLETS INSIDE THE TRAILER. ACID NEUTRALIZER WAS SPRAYED ON THE TRAILER FLOOR AND CONTAMINATED PALLETS, AND THEN WIPED DOWN WITH ABSORBENT PADS. THE TWO DRUMS OF BROKEN BATTERIES AND CLEANUP MATERIAL, ALONG WITH THE REST OF THE PALLETIZED BATTERIES AND SKIDS, WERE PICKED UP BY EAST PEN MANUFACTURING TO BE PROCESSED AT OUR ONSITE SECONDARY LEAD SMELTER FOR RECYCLE.
column169: EAST PENN LOGISTICS, LLC DOES NOT HAVE ANY SUGGESTIONS TO PREVENT RECURRENCE SINCE THIS WAS AN ACCIDENT CAUSED BY ANOTHER. THE BATTERIES WERE CORRECTLY WRAPPED TO THE SKIDS.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS HAULING A LOAD ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, GOING NORTH ON 6TH ST AND MAKING A LEFT TURN ONTO 76TH AVE. NEAR CEDAR RAPIDS, IA. THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO TURN THE CORNER TOO FAST AND THE TRUCK AND TRAILER ROLLED OVER ONTO IT'S RIGHT SIDE ON THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD. WHEN THE TRAILER LANDED ON IT'S SIDE, A PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE ON THE TOP OF THE TRAILER STARTED RELEASING PRESSURE. EMERGENCY PERSONNEL RESPONDED AND MONITORED THE LEAK UNTIL RECOVERY PERSONNEL ARRIVED AND TRANSFERRED CARGO TO ANOTHER TRAILER. AS SOON AS TRANSFER BEGAN, PRESSURE WAS REDUCED AND LEAK STOPPED. RECOVERY PERSONNEL ARRIVED AT THE SCENE ABOUT 4 HOURS AFTER THE ACCIDENT. LOAD WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TRAILER AND UNIT WAS UP-RIGHTED AND TOWED AWAY. NO CLEAN-UP WAS NEEDED AT THE SITE.
column169: THIS ROLLOVER WAS DETERMINED TO BE CAUSED BY EXCESS SPEED WHILE MAKING A CORNER. WE ARE ALSO CONDUCTING DRIVER SAFETY MEETINGS AND PRESENTING THE TRAINING MATERIAL TO ALL OF OUR DRIVERS.

column169: All employees who perform safety sensitive duties have been trained in accordance with the DOT and OSHA regulations. Since this incident, all safety sensitive employees have been retrained on the proper handling of hazardous materials. We have readdressed the importance that all loads are secured from ANY movement in the trailer. A new procedure has been implemented: the dock supervisor on duty will inspect and sign off on all loads of hazardous materials to ensure they are properly loaded and secured. Nothing moves until the supervisor signs off.All drivers are to carry extra straps to insure they have the proper means to secure the load in the trailer. If the driver cannot secure the load they are not to pick up the hazardous materials.

column168: Driver arrived at the Oklahoma City unload station, gauged tanks per protocol to ensure the tanker truck could unload.  The driver began unloading process.  While he was unloading, a second driver arrived at unload station, looked at sign in sheet and asked if he had gauged tanks.  The driver told him that he had. Through some miscommunication, the second driver believed the tank level was at a safe level for him to unload.  He began to unload his trailer.  As driver #1 finished unloading and was putting up his hose, he heard a noise, and saw that oil was coming out of the top of the tanks.  He ran over to tell driver #2, whose view was obscured by his trailer, to shut down his pump, which he did immediately.  Both contacted supervisor immediately per protocol and we went to site to begin investigation and clean up.  Approximately one barrel spilled out the vent top.
column169: Ensure that there is no miscommunication between drivers.  Each driver must gauge on their own and not assume the previous driver had completed the gauging.

column168: AN OVER THE ROAD TRACTOR (OWNED AND OPERATED BY HILCO TRANSPORT, INC.) TRANSPORTING A TANK PORTABLE TANK (TRAILER) LOADED WITH 7300 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON US HIGHWAY 17 NORTH OVER THE ARTHUR RAVENEL BRIDGE IN CHARLESTON, SOUTH CAROLINA. THE HILCO VEHICLE WAS ESTABLISHED AND MAINTAINED IN A ROADWAY TRAVEL LANE. A PRIVATE PASSENGER VEHICLE WAS ALSO TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON US HIGHWAY 17 NORTH OVER THE ARTHUR RAVENEL BRIDGE, IN AN ADJACENT TRAVEL LANE.  THE DRIVER OF THE PRIVATE PASSENGER VEHICLE REPORTEDLY SWERVED TO AVOID A STALLED VEHICLE, DID NOT MAINTAIN LANE CONTROL, AND TRAVELLED INTO THE TRAVEL LANE OCCUPIED BY THE HILCO VEHICLE RESULTING IN A COLLISION WITH THE TANK TRAILER. THE PRIVATE PASSENGER VEHICLE BECAME LODGED UNDER THE HILCO TANK TRAILER.    THE COLLISION RESULTED IN DAMAGE TO THE TANK TRAILER AND THE PIPING ON THE TANK TRAILER. THIS DAMAGE RESULTED IN A RELEASE OF AN ESTIMATED 45 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL FROM THE PIPING ON THE TANK TRAILER. PETROLEUM WAS NOT RELEASED FROM THE BODY OF THE TANK TRAILER DURING THIS INCIDENT. THE RELEASED PETROLEUM IMPACTED THE CONCRETE ROADWAY SURFACE. THE ESTIMATED DURATION OF THE RELEASE WAS 15 MINUTES.    UPON BEING NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT, HILCO TRANSPORT, INC. CONTACT HIGHLANDS ENVIRONMENTAL SOLUTIONS, INC. (HES) FOR SPILL RESPONSE SERVICES. HES DISPATCHED A LOCAL SPILL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO THE SCENE. PETROLEUM PRODUCT IN THE DAMAGED TANK TRAILER WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER HILCO TANK TRAILER. PETROLEUM SORBENT MATERIALS WERE APPLIED TO THE ROADWAY TO CONTAIN AND ABSORB THE RELEASED PETROLEUM. THESE SORBENTS WERE RECOVERED, AND TRANSPORTED OFF-SITE FOR DISPOSAL.
column169: NONE.  NEITHER THE HILCO DRIVER NOR EQUIPMENT WERE FOUND TO HAVE CONTRIBUTED TO THE INCIDENT.

column168: On May 11, 2015 at 08:59 hours, personnel in the CSXT Selkirk yard discovered TILX 350576, a loaded UN 1267, Petroleum Crude Oil tank car with wetness on the sides of the tank car. The tank car was isolated and the shipper UET Shipping, LLC was notified by CHEMTREC, report 2015-05-11-00048, Mr. Clarence Vassau, cell 720-563-7937 was notified of the product release on TILX 350576, a CSXT emergency response contractor, EP+S of Vermont was dispatched to the yard and found product inside the protective housing of the tank car, EPSVT gauged the pressure on the car at 10 psig, with product in the vapor line nozzle. The car was secured for further investigation. On May 19, 2015 CSXT HazMat Manger Michael Bethge inspected TILX 350576, the day time temperature was 62 degrees, the tank car pressure reading was 1.8 psig, and there was fresh oil found on the VRV Midland device valve neck and mounting flange. The manway was not opened as it was suspected to be shell full.  {AAR MSRP M-1002, C-III, Appendix A: 3.10.2 Vacuum relief valves installed prior to July 1, 2013, must be designed to bubble-tight down to the start-to-open pressure and up to 100 psi (689 kPa) positive pressure.  The integrity of the seal must not be affected after opening the valve against 100 psi (689kPa) positive pressure.  The minimum start-to-open pressure must be designed for negative 0.75 psig (5.17 kPag).} Therefore it is recognized that this valve is releasing product due to an overload situation, and the vacuum relief valve is non-compliant with 49 CFR 174.50.  Mr. Clarence Vassau was notified of the non-compliant issue and the overloaded status of this tank car.    This will require an AAR 7.1 form to be filed.  The incident did require a special move to set the tank car out of the K03805 unit train consist.  Cause Code: 1054 (2 points)  NARRI: 5x(5+5+0)x(2+0) = 100
column169: Mr. Clarence Vassau was advised the TILX 350576 would require product removal prior to being forwarded and that the Vacuum Relief Valve would require replacement as that tank car is non-compliant for movement under 49 CFR.

column168: On May 27, 2015 at 10:18 hours personnel in the Norfolk and Southern Cosgrove Yard discovered UTLX 11713 a loaded tank car of Sulfuric Acid leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the National Response Center Report #1117706 was notified along with South Carolina DHEC Report #201502340 and CHEMTREC  Report #2015-05-27-00159were notified. HMS Manager Rob James, a CSXT hazardous materials manager, was dispatched to the scene and found the three bolts for the fill hole less than tool tight. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper (John with Southern State Phone Number 912-232-1101). The bolts on the fill hole were tightened and the car released for transport. The incident did not require a special switching move.      NAR Cause Code: 224- Fill Hole    5 (5+5+1) X (2+0)= 110 NARRI
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On May 26, 2015 at approximately 1820 hours personnel in the CSXT Pinoca Yard discovered UTLX 500006, a loaded tank car of Toluene leaking from the Vapor Line Valve on top of the car. The car was isolated and Marathon Petroleum (Shipper),  and the National Response Center were notified. Chemtrec was not notified because the shipper was notified directly.  Hazmat Manager Rob James was contacted via CSX emergency response number 1-800-232-0144.  Contractor SWS Environmental Services (Bob Baxter), a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a loose vapor line valve leaking product. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Michael Murray Phone number 606-922-4079. Contractor personnel fixed the problem and decontaminated the car. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.      NAR Cause Code: 361 - Air Inlet / Vapor Valve    5(5 + 3 + 0) X (2 + 0) = 80 NARRI
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On May 18, 2015 at 11:09 hours personnel in the CSXT Erwin Yard discovered UTLX 667708, a loaded tank car of Xylenes leaking from the top of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Chevron Phillips Chemical Co, was notified via CHEMTREC Report 2015-05-18-00110.  HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found product leaking from the threaded connection between the tank cars liquid line and the liquid line valve.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative (Jim Mason 806-275-5663).  The liquid line valve was removed, inspected, and reinstalled.  RESCAR, an AAR qualified mobile repair facility, inspected the repairs and performed a bubble leak test prior to allowing the car to continue in transportation.  This release required a special move.  NARRI: 5(5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60  Cause Code: 282
column169: No additional comments.
